	Had Robespierre possessed common courage, he would probably even now have been victorious; but he was wholly unmanned; he wept like an infant, and whined most lamentably about the ingratitude of men. In the mean time, the leaders of the opposite party acted with promptness and decision. Legendre, singly, entered the hall of the jacobins, and by his rude but vigorous eloquence, actually disperesed the, put out the lights, locked the doors, and carried the keys to the convention. Barras and Leonard Bourdon collected some battalions of national guards, and their columsn met at the house of the commune. They ascended the staircase amid shouts of vive la convention, and the reign of Rebespierre was at an end. As another proof of he uncertainty of history, and even of evidence, we may refer to the different ways of narrating one of the most important particular in the fall of this execrable being. His jaw-bone was broken by a pistol-shot:--Who fired it? General report affirmed that it was himself. Mr. Lavallee was told by well-informed men, that it was a gen-d'arme. The Dictionare des Hommes Marquans hints that his brother pulled the trigger. On turning to the Dictionaire Historique, we find the name of the gen d'arme Charles Meda to whom the honour of shooting him is assigned; and to crown this assemblage of contradictions, Bealiue, in his very interesting Essais Historiques, affirms that it was Robespierre himself who fired the pistol, and produces in a note the testimony of the keeper of the hotel de ville, who was of course on the spot, and declares that he had witnessed the act.


http://www.academia.edu/download/46762645/Robespierres_Last_Letter-_A_Final__Failed_Attempt_to_Rally_the_French_People_to_the_Terrors_Cause.docx
	After holing up in Paris’s Hôtel de Ville, Robespierre and his compatriots sent out letters to the forty-eight section of the city, seeking to incite the people of France to rise up in their defense (Scurr, 354). One such letter, now housed in the Carnavalet Museum in Paris, is a direct appeal to the citizens of Robespierre’s own Section des Piques. This document, baring the signatures of four of the Committee’s members (Lerebours, Legrand, Louvet, and Payan) is a simple one, which reads as follows:
		Courage, patriots of the Pike Section, liberty triumphs! Already those whose steadfastness rendered them formidable to traitors are at liberty; everywhere the people are showing themselves worthy of their reputation. The meeting place is at the commune where the brave Hanriot will carry out the orders of the Executive Committee which has been established to save the country (Robespierre et al.)

	Robespierre’s signature was meant to accompany the others, however, it is incomplete. In its place are several splatters of what appears to be blood. They were spilled onto the document, according to legend, from a gunshot wound to Robespierre’s face.

	What, or who, caused the wound has long been a subject of historical debate. Jean Matrat, writing in 1975, denies that the stains are blood, stating that “chemical analysis of the stains has shown them to be ink” (Matrat, 280). However, Matrat offers no source for the results of such a chemical analysis, so one must question such a claim. Ruth Scurr, more cautious in her analysis, offers the opinion that the blood could be that of Robespierre, or that the stain could have been on the document before his arrest, and vomiting caused by an illness, not a gunshot wound, is what caused Robespierre to pause, leaving his signature incomplete (Scurr, 354-355). Paris’s Musée Carnavalet, where the document is housed, states on its website that the blood is that of Robespierre, from a wound caused by a bullet to the jaw ("France: Facsimile of the Call to the People").

	The causes of the stains, and their origins, have been the basis of significant historical conjecture. What has not, however, is the context of the letter. While the letter is one of several similar letters that were sent out in the hours before the arrest of Robespierre and his comrades, this particular letter holds historical significance for several reasons. For example, the letter was addressed to the patriots of Robespierre’s own Section des Piques, a fact that, Thompson notes, is ironic, because Robespierre’s own section of Paris could not be counted on to defend him (Thompson 577). The letter also holds significance because, despite the dubious nature of the stains, there is no doubt that this was the last document that Robespierre had a hand in composing before his execution the next day. 

	...The forces of the National Assembly, guessing at an over simplistic password (Vive Robespierre!) were able to gain entry to the Hôtel de Ville, and, as popular history tells us, captured Robespierre just as he was signing the letter to rally the Section des Piques of Paris. In the melee, Robespierre was wounded, accounting, as some would say, for the stains on the parchment that would serve as his last written dialogue (Thompson, 577). He was arrested, held in the same cell as Mary Antoinette had been before her demise (Andress, 343), and executed without trial on 28 July, 1794. Despite his amazing oratory skills, the letters similar to the one he was signing upon his arrest were simply not enough to rally the poor of Paris back to his, and his allies, side. 

	This letter was written in a time that Robespierre knew he faced imminent death. Without the excesses of both his own rule and those around him, the Revolution in France does not enter its most radical, bloody, phase and the letter is not composed when it is composed. Despite the power that Robespierre held over France (as head of the Jacobins, the de facto leader of the Committee of Public Safety, the President of the National Assembly, and even the secular head of the Cult of the Supreme Being), in the end, his influence could not save him from falling victim to the very Terror that he helped cause. The letters were intended to call upon the people of Paris to rise up and save their wayward saviors, yet, in the end, Paris did not organize, the soldiers of the Commune, disheartened and confused, left, and Robespierre and his cronies were left to defend themselves.

	While historians are left to debate the implications of both the letter itself and the stains on the document, there can be no doubt as to what the letter demonstrates: Robespierre, stripped of all power as a wanted man, was not able to use the gifts he had harnessed to rise to power to save himself. His pleas, in effect, fell on deaf ears, and he was force to face a tide of a revolution that, although set aflame by his own fanning, he was unable to turn back. While my interpretation of the physical circumstances of the letter (Robespierre was signing the letter and was shot in the jaw just before his arrest, accounting for both his incomplete signature and the stains on the parchment) may differ with the views of historians such as Ruth Scurr, Jean Matrat, and J. M. Thompson, one thing can be said without objection: the letter, and what it signified for its intended audience, did not play out as Robespierre intended. Despite the cries for liberty within, the document only signifies the failures of Robespierre and the Committee of Public Safety.


