Peter McPhee, 2012: Convention orders arrest of Hanriot, Dumas, and, other Robespierrist officials, and five deputies: St Just, Couthon, Lebs, Augustin Robespierre and Robespierre. No one wanted to arrest the deputies or officials, and deputies including Hanriot, Lescot-Fleuriot and Payan made it to town hall and had a meeting.

Mayor Lescot Fleuriot called on people Paris to defend Robespierre and crew against Convention conspirators, most of 48 sections made no move but 13 sent batallions to defend the Town Hall against the Convention.

The convention heard they asked for military help and declared the five deputies outlaws. They gathered forces headed by Leonard Bourdon then entered the town hall at 2:30 AM. By then the 13 sections had melted away, and they were able to arrest them.

Augustin Robespierre had jumped from a window in an attempt to escape. Robespierre left an order to his neighborhoods section with an unfinished signature that was spattered in blood, which might have been because Robespierre was uncertain whether or not to attack the Convention ("For was not the Convention the French people itself?"). Lebas had two pistols and some suggest he blew his brains out and Robespierre tried to commit suicide with the other. Others say he was shot by a gendarme while signing the document.

Robespierre wasn't able to speak and gestures he made for a pen and paper were refused.



