C. Knight, The Pictorial History of Englandl, 1843: Bourdon shows up appears to be worried the Robespierrist outlaws will blow up themselves and a chunk of Paris. Some of his people convinced canoneers in front of Hotel de Ville to switch sides and point their guns at the hotel instead.

They previously said they were loyal to Henriot, and when this happened he ran out and tried to convince them to switch back. When this didn't work he ran back to the meeting in council-chamber of the commune and announced all is lost. Coffinhall roared "Villain! and thy cowardice is the cause!" and grabbed Henriot and threw him out the window into a dung heap or a sewer. Augsitn Robespierre threw himself head first out a window, Lebas shot himself with a pistol, Saint-Just clasped a knife but didn't use it, and Couthon crept under a table and hit himself with a blunt weapon but this was ineffectual. Robespierre put a pistol in his mouth to blow out his brains, but when he pulled the trigger it slipped and it broke his jaw and went through is cheek instead. 

Leonard Bourdon burst into the room disguised as a common gendarme and found Robespierre bleeding on a chair with a knife in his hand, Couthon lying under the table as though dead, and some municipal officers apparently getting ready to run. The Gendarmes fired one or two pistol shots, and then all the conspirators quietly submitted to be arrested. They found Henriot covered in filth where he had fallen, adn Augustin found alive with broken limbs and a fractured skull. Some of the armed people (gendarmes or soliders?) dragged Couthon and thought of throwing his body into a river but found he was still alive.

Bourdon told the convention they owe a lot to Gendarme Charles Andrew Meda, who killed two conspirators, grabbed a knife from Robespierre, and struck Couthon who also had a knife.

Shortly after this Legendre entered and told about how he had scattered the Jacobins. By all appearances, most of them dispersed on their own when the learned of the catastrophe of Hotel de ville. But everone this night was eager to show they had been an important actor, and Legendre said he burst into the Jacobin-hall with only 10 self-devoting patriots with a double-barrelled pistol to shoot the conspirator he should find sitting as president. He said the president's name was Vivier, but Vivier mingled with the crowd. Legndre said he asked the crowd to disperse telling them they were misled. They all clapped for Legendre and demanded action against Vivier.

Meanwhile, Robespierre was carried away and put on a table where citizens could look at him. Some gave him pieces of white paper, others mocked and cursed at him. The only words Robespierre spoke were to ask for water and some linen rags.



Thomas Carlyle, 1902: The Canoneers switch to the Convention side with shouting. Then Heriot comes down, some say drunk, and finds the Cannons pointing at him. Previously, the decree outlying the Robespierrists was read to Henriot's troops, and Barras' troops had fratnerised with them and persuaded them, who were already half-hearted. (then according to Carlyle citing d'Hericault, the Communards either tried to kill themselves or awaited arrest passivley).

Henriot stumbled back in drunk and announced "All is lost!" they cried "Miserable, it is thou that hast lost it!" and threw him, or he threw himself, out the window, where he fell into a cesspool. Augustin then exited the window. Saint-Just, they say, asked Lebas to kill him but he wouldn't'. Couthon crept under a table and tried to kill himself but didn't.

When "we" entered the room, found all undone and ready for seizure: Robespeirre sitting on chair with pistol shot through his jaw. Meda says it was he who shot Robespierre, and he got promoted for his services, but this is incredible. The conspirators were gathered up and Henriot and Augustin were fished up.

Robespierre law in an anteroom of the Convention hall and was a spectacle. He was bullied and insulted but spoke no more word in this world. Samson executed him and the crowd, Paris, France, and Europe applauded ever after down to this generation.



Timothy Tackett, 2015: Robespierre and his allies debated what to do. Jean Dyzez said if they acted decicively "all would be lost." Robespierre didn't want to act like a dictator. In the end he did nothing to encourage the Commune or rally the guardsmen outside. Without clear leadership from Robespierre the men outside shouldered their muskets and left when the Convention ordered them to desist. Then two groups of Convention guardesmen led by Bourdon and Barrass broke into the city hall. In the melee, Augistin jumped out a window, Couthon was pushed down the stairs in his weelchar, and Robespierre and Lebas were shot. It is still debated whether or not Lebas and Robespierre had shot themselves.



Antoine de Baecque, 2013: Robespierre, Augustin, Saint-Just, Lebas, Couthon, Hanriot, all see themselves surrounded in the Maison Communie. When the place is attacked, some try to flee, like Hanriot or Couthon, others commit suicide, like Lebas and Augustin, and maybe Robespierre. Was Robespierre shot from his own pistol, from the policeman Charles Merda, or even from two bullets? Scholars have been quaralleing over this for centuries.



Peter Hervé, 1818: When Convention forces entered, Robespierre shot himself in the jaw, St Just asked Lebas to kill him, Lebas killed himself, Couthon went under a table with a knife and wavered but couldn't resolve to stab himself, Augustin threw himself from a casement but was only bruised, Coffinhall threw Henriot out a window and he was lacerated. They were all arrested and carried to the Committee.



George Henry Lewes, 1849: Bourdon marched up to the Place de Greve to shouts of "Vive la Convoition." Henriot galloped around the middle of the crowd like a madman and shouted "Vive la Commune" but contempt fell on him fro his drunken disorderly appearance. Henriot's appearence, the blocked up streets, and the expected arrival of fresh troops all combined to discourage the sectionists, so they turned their cannons against the Hotel de Ville and then dispersed.

There was silence then report of gunshots followed by cries of horror from the Hotel de Ville. Committee of General Safety agent Dulac at the head of 25 sappers and some grenadiers beat down the doors with hatches and went upstairs.

Robespierre and his friends heard them coming upstairs and Lebas gives him a pistol. Robespierre refuses to commit suicide and Saint Just and Couthon side with him. As they hear troops approaching, Lebas shoots himself in heart and falls into the arms of Augustin, who jumps out the window. Coffinhal stomps around and throws Henriot out a window and yells at him for being drunk.

Meanwhile Bourdon goes upstairs himself with five gendarmes and some soldiers. Dulac joins them and they force down the door. They see Robespierre sitting at a table. Bourbon grabs Meda's arm, points at him and says "that's the man!" and Meda shoots him in the face, who drops on the table and stains with blood the proclamation with his unfinished signature. Couthon tries to get up with bad legs but staggers under the table. Saint Just sits there muornfully and defiantly.

Robespeirre is taken to a room in Place de la Revolution and some citizens see him. They search his pocket and find a brace of loaded pistols with the arms of France engraved on them. They also found 400 pounds on him but Lews stresses "There is no reason to suppose this money belonged to him. It was in all probability pubhc money, and about to be applied to public use." (?) They carried Robespierre away and executed him and everyone cheered.



Washington Irving and/or Lavellee, 1817: Robespierre cried like a baby. Meanwhile, Legendre entered the hall of Jacobins and dispersed the crowd, locked the door, and carried the keys to the convention. Barras and Bourden went upstairs with some soldiers and the reign of Robespierre was over. There are many different accounts of who shot Robespierre--General report said it was himself, Lavallee was told it was a gendarme, the Dictionar ydes Hommes Marquans hints it was Augustin, and the Dictionare Historique says it was Meda. Beliue in his Essais Historiques says Robespierre did it, and includes a note of the testimony of the keeper of the hotel de ville, who was of course on the spot, who said he had witnessed the act.



Martin Smith: Robespiere and his compatriots were sending out letters to the 48 sections of the city at Hotel de Ville asking them to rise up to their defense. On the letter to his own section, Robespeierre's signature was incomplete with splatters of what look like blood in its place. According to legend, these were split by a gunshot wound to his face.

The cause of the stains and their origins are a subject of historical debate. Matrat said chemical analysis shows they were ink but he didn't cite any source. Scurr says maybe the stain was on the paper already and Robespier stopped in the middle of writing his signature to vomit. The Paris meuseum where the doc is held says the blood was Robospieree's from a bullet to his jaw.

The letter was to Robospierre's own section, but his section could not be counted on to defend him.

The National Assembly forces guessed the password "Vive Robespierre!" and entered Hotel de Ville, where, as popular history tells us, they captured Robespiere just as he was signing the letter. Some say Robespierre being wounded in the melee accounts for the stain on the letter.

Despite his amazing oratory skills, Robespiere's letters weren't enough to rally the poor of Paris back to his and his allies side. Paris did not organize and the soldiers of the Commune were disheartened and confused and left.

Smith thinks the stains were from blood from a shot to Robespierre's jaw. Despite calls for liberty, the letter only signifies the failures of Robespierre and the Committee of Public Safety.


(picture of letter: https://www.tripadvisor.com/LocationPhotoDirectLink-g187147-d2038979-i175728261-Paris_Charms_Secrets_Tours-Paris_Ile_de_France.html)


James Matthew Thompson, 1952: During the night, Robespierre's crew made a last effort to arouse the Sections. Henriot rode around but people didn't understand him. He was drunk and got arrested. Then he was released from gaol by 200 National Guards.

The streets around the City Hall were crowded with people ready to be led if Robespierre's friends had been alert, but there was no leader. Many groups, National Guards were still loyal, but there was no real effort made to unite them against the Convention.

Robespierre and his companions listened to the shouts outside then all was silent, then they heard approaching footsteps and clinking of arms. St Just asked Lebas to kill him, Lebas killed himself, Couthon tried to open his veins, and Coffin Hal and Augustin jumped out the windows.

It might always be a mooted question whether or not Robespierre shot himself, but commonly accepted account is that Bourdon pointed him out and Meda shot him, splatting blood on the paper he had was in the middle of signing. The paper said "the country is imminent danger ... to arms! to arms!" If this spirited appeal was published, it might have saved the day, but the nerve of Robespierre failed at this critical point.

Robespierre was carried to another room and laid on a table. The comittee sent a surgeon and St Just watched over him. Couthon was weak from blood loss and Augustin suffered from a broken leg. Henriot had taken refuge in a sewer but was fished out. Coffin Hal escaped after leaping from the window but was arrested a few days later and executed. Lerebours avoided pursuit and reached Switzerland in safety.

A bunch of people and clerks from adjoining offices came in and made fun of Robespiere and poked him. Legendre laughed and said he is greedy and now emperor of a table and Robespier replied "silence butcher of bullocks!"

Robespierre wiped his mouth on holster flap of pistols who case coincidentally bore the inscription "The Great Monarch; Lecourt, Maker to the King." An on-looker gave him some setts of paper to wipe the blood from his lips, and Robespierre replied "Je vous remercie, Monsier." Strangley, in his last moments he renounced the Jacobin for of speech he had been accustomed to and that he had assdiuously used since its introduction.

Someone placed a cup of vinegar and a sponge near him, no doubt moved by sympathy. Robespierre moistened his swollen and feverish lips. Not a word escaped him as he suffered with the fortitude of a Stoic. Barras wrote in his memoirs that some of Robespierre's teeth fell to the floor and he and a gunner fought over them.

Augustine, Couthon (covered in blood), Henriot, and Robespierre were carted to be executed. They stopped at Madame Aigne's funeral, who had killed herself the day before from fear of Robespierre, so it was rumored.

The execution ripped off Robespierre's bandage and he roared in pain because his jaw fell. All were executed, the closing act of the great terror. Now, each citizen wondered what would be the next act in the drama.



